# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-award-for-science-diplomacy] The **AAAS David and Betty Hamburg Award for Science Diplomacy** (2022–), formerly the **AAAS Award for Science Diplomacy** (2010–2021) and **Award for International Scientific Cooperation** (1992–2009), is awarded by the American Association for the Advancement of Science (AAAS).
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-award-for-science-diplomacy] After the 2021 presentation, the award was renamed in honor of psychiatrists David A.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-award-for-science-diplomacy] The award offers a monetary prize of $2,500, a certificate of citation, and travel expenses to attend the AAAS annual meeting to receive the award.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-award-for-scientific-freedom-and-responsibility] The establishment of this new Award for Scientific Freedom and Responsibility was announced by AAAS executive officer William D.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-award-for-scientific-freedom-and-responsibility] The award, presented for the first time at the 1982 AAAS Annual Meeting in Washington, DC, consisted of a plaque and a cash prize of $1,000.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize] The prize is named after nuclear physicist Philip Abelson.The award consists of an engraved medallion and an honorarium of $5,000.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] AAAS was the first permanent organization established to promote science and engineering nationally and to represent the interests of American researchers from across all scientific fields.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] It is the world's largest general scientific society, with over 120,000 members, and is the publisher of the well-known scientific journal *Science*.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The American Association for the Advancement of Science was created on September 20, 1848, at the Academy of Natural Sciences in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] According to the first constitution which was agreed to at the September 20 meeting, the goal of the society was to promote scientific dialogue in order to allow for greater scientific collaboration.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] By doing so, the association aimed to use resources to conduct science with increased efficiency and allow for scientific progress at a greater rate.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The association also sought to increase the resources available to the scientific community through active advocacy of science.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] There were only 78 members when the AAAS was formed.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] As a member of the new scientific body, Matthew Fontaine Maury, USN was one of those who attended the first 1848 meeting.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] At a meeting held on Friday afternoon, September 22, 1848, Redfield presided, and Matthew Fontaine Maury gave a full scientific report on his *Wind and Current Charts*.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Maury stated that hundreds of ship navigators were now sending abstract logs of their voyages to the United States Naval Observatory.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] He added, "Never before was such a corps of observers known." But, he pointed out to his fellow scientists, his critical need was for more "simultaneous observations".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] "The work," Maury stated, "is not exclusively for the benefit of any nation or age".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Coffin of Easton, Pennsylvania, and Professor Stephen Alexander of Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] This was scientific cooperation, and Maury went back to Washington with great hopes for the future.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] In 1850, the first female members were accepted: astronomer Maria Mitchell and entomologist Margaretta Morris.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Science educator Almira Hart Lincoln Phelps was elected in 1859.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] By 1860, membership increased to over 2,000.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Although the AAAS became dormant during the American Civil War (their August 1861 meeting in Nashville, Tennessee, was postponed indefinitely after the outbreak of the first major engagement of the war at Bull Run), the association recovered after the end of the hostilities.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] In 1866, Frederick Barnard presided over the first meeting of the resurrected AAAS at a meeting in New York City.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Following the revival of the AAAS, the group had considerable growth.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The AAAS permitted all people, regardless of scientific credentials, to join.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The AAAS did, however, institute a policy of granting the title of "Fellow of the AAAS" to well-respected scientists within the organization.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Also, the reputation of the AAAS was somewhat tarnished, because its 3rd president Alexander Dallas Bache used the Society as a lobbying tool for his agency, the US Coast Survey.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Several prominent scientists lost interest in the AAAS, and the society's influence declined.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The next turning point in the AAAS history was the partnership with journal *Science*, which became the society's official publication in 1900, and provided the AAAS with some revenue through subscription and advertising.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The AAAS become the sole owner of *Science* in 1946.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Another important event for the society was the establishment of its Congressional Fellowship program in 1973, which was kick-started by a US$10,000 donation from William T.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Leshner, AAAS CEO from 2001 until 2015, published many op-ed articles discussing how many people integrate science and religion in their lives.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] He has opposed the insertion of non-scientific content, such as creationism or intelligent design, into the scientific curriculum of schools.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] In February 2007, the AAAS used satellite images to document human rights abuses in Burma.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The next year, AAAS launched the Center for Science Diplomacy to advance both science and the broader relationships among partner countries, by promoting science diplomacy and international scientific cooperation.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] In 2012, AAAS published op-eds, held events on Capitol Hill and released analyses of the U.S. federal research-and-development budget, to warn that a budget sequestration would have severe consequences for scientific progress.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] AAAS covers various areas of sciences and engineering.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] It has 24 sections, each with a committee and its chair.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] These committees are also entrusted with the annual evaluation and selection of Fellows.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The most recent Constitution of the AAAS, enacted on January 1, 1973, establishes that the governance of the AAAS is accomplished through four entities: a President, a group of administrative officers, a Council, and a board of directors.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Individuals elected to the presidency of the AAAS hold a three-year term in a unique way.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The first year is spent as president-elect, the second as president and the third as chairperson of the board of directors.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] In accordance with the convention followed by the AAAS, presidents are referenced by the year in which they left office.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Geraldine Richmond is the president of AAAS for 2015–16; Phillip Sharp is the board chair; and Barbara A.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Each took office on the last day of the 2015 AAAS Annual Meeting in February 2015.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] On the last day of the 2016 AAAS Annual Meeting, February 15, 2016, Richmond will become the chair, Schaal will become the president, and a new president-elect will take office.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Past presidents of AAAS have included some of the most important scientific figures of their time.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Among them: explorer and geologist John Wesley Powell (1888); astronomer and physicist Edward Charles Pickering (1912); anthropologist Margaret Mead (1975); and biologist Stephen Jay Gould (2000).
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] There are three classifications of high-level administrative officials that execute the basic, daily functions of the AAAS.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] These are the executive officer, the treasurer and then each of the AAAS's section secretaries.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The current CEO of AAAS and executive publisher of *Science* magazine is Sudip Parikh.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The current Editor in Chief of Science magazine is Holden Thorp.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The AAAS has 24 "sections" with each section being responsible for a particular concern of the AAAS.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] AAAS affiliates include 262 societies and academies of science, serving more than 10 million members, from the Acoustical Society of America to the Wildlife Society, as well as non-mainstream groups like the Parapsychological Association.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The council is composed of the members of the Board of Directors, the retiring section chairmen, elected delegates and affiliated foreign council members.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Among the elected delegates there are always at least two members from the National Academy of Sciences and one from each region of the country.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The President of the AAAS serves as the Chairperson of the council.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Members serve the council for a term of three years.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The council meets annually to discuss matters of importance to the AAAS.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] They have the power to review all activities of the Association, elect new fellows, adopt resolutions, propose amendments to the Association's constitution and bylaws, create new scientific sections, and organize and aid local chapters of the AAAS.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The Council recently has new additions to it from different sections which include many youngsters as well.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] John Kerry of Chicago is the youngest American in the council and Akhil Ennamsetty of India is the youngest foreign council member.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The board of directors is composed of a chairperson, the president, and the president-elect along with eight elected directors, the executive officer of the association and up to two additional directors appointed by elected officers.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Members serve a four-year term except for directors appointed by elected officers, who serve three-year terms.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The current chairman is Gerald Fink, Margaret and Herman Sokol Professor at Whitehead Institute, MIT.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Fink will serve in the post until the end of the 2016 AAAS Annual Meeting, 15 February 2016.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The board of directors has a variety of powers and responsibilities.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] It is charged with the administration of all association funds, publication of a budget, appointment of administrators, proposition of amendments, and determining the time and place of meetings of the national association.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The board may also speak publicly on behalf of the association.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The board must also regularly correspond with the council to discuss their actions.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The AAAS council elects every year, its members who are distinguished scientifically, to the grade of fellow (**FAAAS**).
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Election to AAAS is an honor bestowed by their peers and elected fellows are presented with a certificate and rosette pin.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Formal meetings of the AAAS are numbered consecutively, starting with the first meeting in 1848.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Meetings were not held 1861–1865 during the American Civil War, and also 1942–1943 during World War II.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Since 1946, one meeting has occurred annually, now customarily in February.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Each year, the AAAS gives out a number of honorary awards, most of which focus on science communication, journalism, and outreach – sometimes in partnership with other organizations.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The awards recognize "scientists, journalists, and public servants for significant contributions to science and to the public's understanding of science".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The awards are presented each year at the association's annual meeting.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] These policy fellows spend one or two years working for the executive (130 positions), legislative (5 positions) or judicial (1 position) branches.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The society's flagship publication is *Science*, a weekly interdisciplinary scientific journal.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Other peer-reviewed journals published by the AAAS in the "*Science* family of journals" are *Science Signaling*, *Science Translational Medicine*, *Science Immunology*, *Science Robotics* and the interdisciplinary *Science Advances*.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] They also publish the non-peer-reviewed *Science & Diplomacy*.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] The society previously published the review journal *Science Books & Films* (SB&F).
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] AAAS also publishes on behalf of other organizations through the Science Partner Journals (SPJ) program, with a focus on online-only open access journals.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] SciLine is a philanthropically funded and editorially independent service for journalists and scientists.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Its launch was announced in an October 27, 2017 article in Science by founding director Rick Weiss, former communications chief at the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy and science reporter at the Washington Post.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Its stated mission is to increase the amount and quality of research-backed evidence in news stories by connecting U.S. journalists to scientists and to validated scientific information.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Reporters in the United States can access SciLine's services, which include expert-matching, general media briefings, expert quote sheets, and quick fact sheets.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] As of July 2021, SciLine had fulfilled approximately 2,000 requests from 650 journalists through its expert-matching service.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] SciLine's financial supporters include the Quadrivium Foundation, the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative, the John S. and James L.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Knight Foundation, the Rita Allen Foundation, and the Heinz Endowments.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] In 1996, AAAS launched the **EurekAlert!** website, an editorially independent nonprofit news release distribution service covering all areas of science, medicine and technology.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] EurekAlert! provides news in English, Spanish, French, German, Portuguese, Japanese, and, from 2007, in Chinese.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Working staff journalists and freelancers who meet eligibility guidelines can access the latest studies before publication and obtain embargoed information in compliance with the U.S.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] Securities and Exchange Commission's Regulation Fair Disclosure policy.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] By early 2018, more than 14,000 reporters from more than 90 countries have registered for free access to embargoed materials.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] More than 5,000 active public information officers from 2,300 universities, academic journals, government agencies, and medical centers are credentialed to provide new releases to reporters and the public through the system.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] In 1998, European science organizations countered Eurekalert! with a press release distribution service AlphaGalileo.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/aaas-prize-for-behavioral-science-research] EurekAlert! has fallen under criticism for lack of press release standards and for generating churnalism.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] Jones was elected a member of the National Academy of Engineering (1994) for contributions to the theory and implementation of software systems and for extensive public service.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] Jones' father, a petroleum engineer, encouraged her to pursue a career that would make a difference in the world.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] He taught her to play chess, helped her on geometry problems, and on weekends took her and her younger brother fishing for catfish, red snapper, and trout on Galveston Bay.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] Jones' mother, who had trained as a ballerina and danced in several Hollywood films, taught her daughter a love of painting.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] Born in Fort Worth, Texas and raised in Houston, Anita graduated as valedictorian of her high school class in 1960.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] Jones received an A.B. from Rice University in Mathematics in 1964, a Master of Arts in English Literature from the University of Texas at Austin, in 1968, and a Ph.D. in computer science from Carnegie Mellon University in 1973.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] While at Carnegie Mellon, she met her future husband, William A.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] Jones remained at Carnegie Mellon as an assistant professor, with promotion to associate professor in 1978.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] Wulf, her husband, Jones was a founder and vice president of Tartan Laboratories, a compiler technology company, in 1981.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] The company was later sold to Texas Instruments.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] She joined the faculty of the University of Virginia in 1989, but took leave in June 1993 to become the Director of Defense Research and Engineering for the U.S.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] Department of Defense, a position in which she was responsible for the management of the science and technology program.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] Her responsibilities included the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency and oversight of the Department of Defense laboratories, as well as being the principal advisor to the Secretary of Defense for defense-related scientific and technical matters.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] At the time, it was the highest technical job ever held by a woman in the Department of Defense.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] She returned to the University of Virginia in 1997.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] In the field of computer software systems and cyber-security, Dr.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] Jones has published more than 40 technical articles and two books.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] In 2010, she officially retired but remains involved in the university and continues to mentor young women in technical fields.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] Since 2004, Jones has been a member of the MIT Corporation.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] From 1988 to 1992, she was a trustee of the MITRE Corporation.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] She is a member of the National Academy of Engineering, the Council on Foreign Relations, the National Science Foundation's National Science Board, and the American Philosophical Society.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] Jones received the Augusta Ada Lovelace Award from the Association of Women in Computing in 2004.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] She is also the recipient of the Computing Research Association's Service Award, the Air Force Meritorious Civilian Service Award, and the Department of Defense Award for Distinguished Public Service.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] Navy has named a seamount in the North Pacific Ocean (51° 25’ N and 159° 10’ W) for her.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] In 2007, she was the recipient of the IEEE Founders Medal.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] Jones was also awarded the American Association for the Advancement of Science (AAAS)'s 2012 Philip Hauge Abelson award.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] This award recognizes public servants who have contributed substantially to advancing science.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anita-k-jones] Jones was awarded the AAAS Philip Hauge Abelson Award for her public service roles throughout her career, including her roles on the National Science Board, the National Academies' Policy Division Advisory Council, and the DOD Defense Science Board.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci graduated from the College of the Holy Cross, where he studied classics, and earned his Doctor of Medicine from Cornell University.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] As a physician with the National Institutes of Health (NIH), Fauci served the American public health sector for more than fifty years and has acted as an advisor to every U.S. president since Ronald Reagan.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] During his time as director of the NIAID, he made contributions to HIV/AIDS research and other immunodeficiency diseases, both as a research scientist and as the head of the NIAID.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] During the COVID-19 pandemic, Fauci served under President Donald Trump as one of the lead members of the White House Coronavirus Task Force.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] His advice was frequently contradicted by Trump, and Trump's supporters alleged that Fauci was trying to politically undermine Trump's run for reelection.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] During the Biden administration, Fauci served as one of the lead members of the White House COVID-19 Response Team and as Biden's chief medical advisor.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci was born on December 24, 1940, in Brooklyn, New York City, to Stephen A.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] (1910–2008) and Eugenia Lillian (*née* Abys; 1909–1965) Fauci as the younger of two children.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] His father, a pharmacist, attended Columbia University and owned a drug store.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci worked with his mother and sister at the pharmacy's register and also delivered prescriptions.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] The pharmacy was located in the Dyker Heights section of Brooklyn; it was directly beneath the family apartment, which was previously in the Bensonhurst neighborhood.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] When he was a child, Fauci developed a fascination with World War II, and played basketball and baseball.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci's grandparents immigrated to the United States from Italy in the late 19th century.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] His paternal grandparents, Antonino Fauci and Calogera Guardino, were from Sciacca, Sicily, and his maternal grandparents were from Naples.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] His maternal grandmother, Raffaella Trematerra, was a seamstress and his maternal grandfather, Giovanni Abys, was a Swiss-born artist noted for his landscape and portrait painting, magazine illustrations in Italy, as well as graphic design for commercial labels.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci attended Regis High School, a competitive Jesuit school on Manhattan's Upper East Side, where he captained the school's basketball team despite standing only 5 ft 7 in (1.70 m) tall.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] He decided halfway through high school to become a physician.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] After graduating in 1958, Fauci enrolled at the College of the Holy Cross in Worcester, Massachusetts, where he studied classical Greek and worked in a construction gang during the summers.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci graduated from Holy Cross in 1962 with a Bachelor of Arts in classics on a pre-med track.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci then attended medical school at Cornell University, where he graduated first in his class with a Doctor of Medicine (M.D.) from the Cornell Medical College in 1966.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] At Cornell, he focused on adult internal medicine, mainly infectious diseases and the immune system.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci then did an internship and residency in internal medicine at New York Hospital-Cornell Medical Center (now Weill Cornell Medical Center).
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] After completing his medical residency in 1968, Fauci joined the National Institutes of Health (NIH) as a clinical associate in the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases's (NIAID) Laboratory of Clinical Investigation (LCI).
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] He became head of the LCI's Clinical Physiology Section in 1974, and in 1980 was appointed chief of the NIAID's Laboratory of Immunoregulation.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] He became director of the NIAID in 1984.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci has been offered the position of director of the NIH several times, but has declined each time.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci has been at the forefront of U.S. efforts to contend with viral diseases like HIV/AIDS, SARS, the Swine flu, MERS, Ebola, and COVID-19.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] He played a significant role in the early 2000s in creating the President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR) and in driving development of biodefense drugs and vaccines following the 9/11 terrorist attacks.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci has been a visiting professor at many medical centers and has received numerous honorary doctorates from universities in the U.S. and abroad.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci has made important scientific observations that contributed to the understanding of the regulation of the human immune response and is recognized for delineating the mechanisms whereby immunosuppressive agents adapt to that response.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] He developed therapies for formerly fatal diseases such as polyarteritis nodosa, granulomatosis with polyangiitis, and lymphomatoid granulomatosis.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci discovered how to re-dose cancer drugs in a way that turned a 98 percent mortality rate of the disorder vasculitis into a 93 percent remission rate.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci has contributed to the understanding of how HIV destroys the body's natural defense system, progressing to AIDS.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] He has outlined the mechanisms of induction of HIV expression by endogenous cytokines.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci has worked to develop strategies for the therapy and immune reconstitution of patients with the disease, as well as for a vaccine to prevent HIV infection.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] His current research is concentrated on identifying the nature of the immunopathogenic mechanisms of HIV infection and the scope of the body's immune responses to HIV.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In a 2020 interview with *The Guardian*, Fauci remarked, "My career and my identity has really been defined by HIV." He was one of the leading researchers during the AIDS epidemic in the early 1980s.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In 1981, he and his team of researchers began looking for a vaccine or treatment for this novel virus, though they would meet a number of obstacles.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In October 1988, protesters came to the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci, who had become the institute's director in 1984, bore the brunt of the anger from the LGBTQ+ community who were largely ignored by the government.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Leading AIDS activist Larry Kramer attacked Fauci relentlessly in the media.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] He called him an "incompetent idiot" and a "pill-pushing" tool of the medical establishment.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci did not have control over drug approval though many people felt he was not doing enough.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci did make an effort in the late 1980s to reach out to the LGBTQ+ community in New York and San Francisco to find ways he and the NIAID could find a solution.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci was also praised for engaging with AIDS advocates, and he helped to make experimental AIDS treatments more accessible.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Though Fauci was initially admonished for his treatment of the AIDS epidemic, his work in the community was eventually acknowledged.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Kramer, who had spent years hating Fauci for his treatment of the HIV/AIDS epidemic, eventually called him "the only true and great hero" among government officials during the AIDS crisis.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci was criticized over what some said was a delayed response from the U.S. government to the HIV/AIDS epidemic, including delays in the promotion of experimental HIV/AIDS drugs.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci was the main architect of President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR), an HIV/AIDS program responsible for saving over 20 million lives in the developing world.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In a meeting with reporters on September 17, 2009, Fauci predicted that the H1N1 virus causing the 2009 swine flu pandemic could infect as many as one in three Americans, more than the amount of Americans usually infected by the seasonal flu.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] According to *The Washington Post*, before the COVID-19 pandemic, Fauci was "mostly unknown outside the medical community".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci did not meet with Trump until three years after he was inaugurated as president.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci was a member of the White House Coronavirus Task Force established in late January 2020, under President Donald Trump, to deal with the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] He was described as the administration's public health spokesperson during the pandemic, and a strong advocate for ongoing social distancing efforts in the United States.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In interviews on January 21, January 26, and February 17, Fauci commented on COVID-19.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] He said that at the time of the interviews ("right now"), COVID-19 was not a "major threat" to the American public, with the risk to the American public being "low", but that it was "an evolving situation", and that "public health officials need to take [COVID-19] very seriously".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In the latter interview, Fauci said that COVID-19 could become a "global pandemic which would then have significant implications for" the United States.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In March 2020, he predicted that the infection fatality rate would likely be close to 1%, which was ten times more severe than the 0.1% reported rate for seasonal flu.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In a March 8, 2020, interview, Fauci stated that "right now in the United States, people [who are not infected] should not be walking around with masks", but "if you want to do it, that's fine".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In the same interview, Fauci said that buying masks "could lead to a shortage of masks for the people who really need" them: "When you think masks, you should think of healthcare providers needing them".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] When Fauci made this comment, America's top surgical mask maker was struggling to produce enough masks to meet the increased demand.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] On April 3, the CDC reversed course, quoting recent studies that showed asymptomatic transmission of the virus, thus advocating for the public to wear non-surgical masks to reduce community transmission while Fauci advocated for wearing facial coverings in public.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci's shifting advice on wearing face masks drew criticism, which Fauci responded to by arguing that changes in policy were necessary as scientists learned more about COVID-19.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci's comments were met with a hostile response from former Republican congressional candidate DeAnna Lorraine.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Trump retweeted Lorraine's response, which included the call to "#FireFauci".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] "Fire Fauci" has also been chanted by anti-lockdown protesters in various locations, including Florida and Texas.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] As a result, the White House denied that Trump was firing Fauci, and blamed the media for overreacting.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci was criticized by right-wing pundits and received death threats that necessitated a security detail.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In an interview with *60 Minutes* in 2020, he mentioned that other members of his family, including his wife and daughters, had been repeatedly harassed since the pandemic began.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In June 2020, Fauci said that he was "very concerned" that the ongoing protests against police brutality would cause "surges" in COVID-19 cases, stating that the "large crowds" are a "perfect set-up" for the virus to spread.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In July 2020, Fauci advised the public to "avoid crowds of any type".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] On July 6, 2020, Fauci spoke on a Facebook livestream, offering his opinion that the country's situation pertaining to COVID-19 "is really not good", pointing to more than 55,000 new cases on July 4, 2020.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] He said the United States was "still knee-deep in the first wave" of cases, and was experiencing a "resurgence of infections".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] After this appearance by Fauci, the White House cancelled three media appearances that had been scheduled for him later that week.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] On July 7, 2020, Trump contradicted Fauci's comments describing a dire situation in the country, with Trump saying: "I think we are in a good place.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] I disagree with [Fauci]." While there were disagreements, Trump also at times praised Fauci.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] On July 9, 2020, Trump publicly opined that Fauci "is a nice man, but he's made a lot of mistakes." By July 12, 2020, a White House official told media outlets that "several White House officials are concerned about the number of times Dr.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci has been wrong on things", passing to the media a list of purported mistakes made by Fauci during the outbreak.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] As late as September 23, 2020, when U.S. coronavirus fatalities exceeded 200,000, conservatives continued to question Fauci's and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's (CDC) recommendations for responding to the pandemic.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci said the recommendations remained valid.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Paul had made numerous claims about herd immunity, Sweden's interventions to combat the pandemic, the contention that the populations of Asian countries have greater resilience against COVID-19, and statements about death rates due to the virus.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci would have several intense exchanges with Paul.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In October 2020, Fauci objected after his words, "I can't imagine that anybody could be doing more" were featured in an advertisement from the Trump campaign touting Trump's handling of the pandemic.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci said he did not consent to the ad, his words were taken out of context (he was actually referring to how hard the Coronavirus Task Force was working), and he had never made a political endorsement in his career.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Also, in October, Fauci criticized the Great Barrington Declaration's "focused protection" herd immunity strategy, calling it "total nonsense" and saying that it would lead to many avoidable deaths.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] And if you talk to anybody who has any experience in epidemiology and infectious diseases, they will tell you that that is risky, and you'll wind up with many more infections of vulnerable people, which will lead to hospitalizations and deaths.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] On October 18, 2020, Fauci mentioned that he "wasn't surprised" Donald Trump contracted COVID-19.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] The next day, during a presidential call, Trump called Fauci "a disaster" and said that "people are tired of COVID." During a campaign rally in Phoenix, Arizona, on October 19, Trump launched attacks on his political rival Joe Biden, saying that Biden "wants to listen to Dr.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci" regarding the handling of the pandemic, upon which Biden merely replied "Yes" on Twitter.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] On October 31, *The Washington Post* published an extensive interview with Fauci, in which he voiced a candid assessment of the administration's COVID-19 policies and was critical of the influence of presidential advisor Scott Atlas.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Shortly after midnight on November 2, 2020, Trump insinuated he would fire Fauci "after the election" while on stage at a campaign rally at Miami-Opa Locka Executive Airport in Opa-locka, Florida.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] At the rally, he made false claims that the pandemic was "rounding the turn" and was met by audience chants of "Fire Fauci!", to which he responded, "Don't tell anybody, but let me wait until after the election ...
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] I appreciate the advice." Despite the rhetoric, Fauci was not fired.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] On December 2, the United Kingdom became the first western country to license a vaccine against the coronavirus (Pfizer-BioNTech).
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) was proceeding "the correct way" and said the UK "really rushed through that approval".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] The next day Fauci apologized, telling the BBC "I have a great deal of confidence in what the UK does both scientifically and from a regulator standpoint.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Our process is one that takes more time than it takes in the UK ...
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] On January 3, 2021, President Trump tweeted, "The number of cases and deaths of the China Virus is far exaggerated in the United States because of [the CDC's] ridiculous method of determination compared to other countries".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] That same morning, Fauci responded in an interview on NBC's *Meet the Press*, "The numbers are real.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] We are averaging two- to three thousand deaths per day.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] All you need to do ... is go into the trenches, go into the hospitals, go into the intensive care units and see what is happening.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] The fact that it was outdoors is a little bit better than if they were indoors completely.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] On January 23, 2021, Fauci was quoted saying that letting the science speak on the pandemic got him "into a little bit of trouble" and got "push-back from people in the White House, including the president", during the Trump administration.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] On December 3, 2020, President-elect Joe Biden asked Fauci, in addition to remaining in his role as director of the NIAID, to serve as the chief medical advisor to the president in the Biden administration.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] After the inauguration of Joe Biden in January 2021, Fauci said he experienced a "liberating feeling" in being able to speak freely about science without interference from the new administration.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] He pictured Biden's administration as committed to being "completely transparent, open and honest".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci was involved in the development of the Biden administration's plan for a nationwide COVID-19 vaccine rollout.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In early April 2021, Fauci said of the current situation in the United States that "It's almost a race between getting people vaccinated and this surge that seems to want to increase".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In early May 2021, when asked if the CDC's summer camp guidance was excessive, Fauci responded by saying that "I wouldn't call them excessive, but they certainly are conservative" and added that the guidance "looks a bit strict" and "a bit stringent".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Also in early May, Fauci said that he is "not convinced" that COVID-19 originated naturally and that "we should continue to investigate what went on in China until we continue to find out to the best of our ability what happened".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In mid-May 2021, Fauci said that Americans who are fully vaccinated against COVID-19 no longer need to wear masks outdoors, except for in "completely crowded situations".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] This guidance was updated in July 2021 to recommend that all people wear masks regardless of vaccination status, in what Fauci said was due to the much more contagious Delta variant.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In May 2021, Fauci denied that the National Institutes of Health supported "gain-of-function research" at the Wuhan Institute of Virology.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In early June 2021, over 3,000 internal government emails sent by Fauci from January to June 2020 were obtained by media outlets through Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) requests.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] These emails contain information about how the United States and Fauci initially responded to COVID-19.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] On June 22, 2021, Fauci said that the SARS-CoV-2 Delta variant is the "greatest threat" to eliminating COVID-19 in the United States.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In December 2021, Fauci, along with virologist Jeffery K.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In February 2022, Fauci told the *Financial Times* that "As we get out of the full-blown pandemic phase of Covid-19, which we are certainly heading out of, these decisions will increasingly be made on a local level rather than centrally decided or mandated.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In March 2022, Fauci said that the United States should expect an increase in COVID-19 cases from the BA.2 subvariant of Omicron, but that it might not lead to a severe increase in hospitalizations and deaths.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] On April 27, 2022, Fauci said that the United States was "out of the full-blown explosive pandemic phase" of COVID-19.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] On May 15, 2022, Fauci said that he would resign if Donald Trump won the 2024 U.S. presidential election.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] On August 22, 2022, Fauci announced his intention to step down from his position in December "to pursue the next chapter" of his career.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] He resigned from his position on December 31 of that same year.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] On January 20, 2025, President Biden issued Fauci a preemptive pardon covering potential federal offenses between January 1, 2014, and January 20, 2025.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] The AP reported that the pardons were intended to guard against potential “revenge” by the incoming Trump administration, while Biden said they were intended to protect public servants from what he described as politically motivated prosecutions.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Other news outlets described the pardon as an “unprecedented use” of the president’s clemency powers.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] On June 26, 2023, Georgetown University announced that Fauci would join its faculty as a distinguished professor, teaching in both the School of Medicine and McCourt School of Public Policy, effective July 1.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] On February 7, 2025, the United States Department of Health and Human Services terminated a $168,000 contract for a Fauci museum exhibit at the National Institutes of Health.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Owing to his prominent role in the United States' response to numerous global pandemics, most notably HIV/AIDS and COVID-19, Fauci has become the subject of tributes and interpretations across various media, including television, literature, merchandising, and internet memes.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Author Sally Quinn has credited Fauci as the inspiration for the love interest to the protagonist in her bestselling 1991 romance novel *Happy Endings*.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Anthony Della Vida on Fauci in his play *The Destiny of Me*.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Brad Pitt's performance as Fauci during the 2020 season of *Saturday Night Live* earned the actor an Emmy nomination, and praise from Fauci.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In the spring of 2020 amidst the COVID-19 pandemic, bakeries across the United States began selling pastries, particularly donuts, with Fauci's face on them to pay tribute to his work in the public health sector.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In September 2021, *Fauci*, a documentary film about Fauci's life and career, was released by Magnolia Pictures.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] The film was produced by National Geographic Documentary Films.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In November 2021, Skyhorse released a book by anti-vaccine activist Robert F.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Kennedy Jr. titled *The Real Anthony Fauci: Bill Gates, Big Pharma, and the Global War on Democracy and Public Health*.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In response, Fauci described the author as "a very disturbed individual".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci is a longtime resident of Washington, D.C.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] *The Washington Post* reported in 2022 that he has lived in the same "comfortable but modest house since 1977".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In 1985, he married Christine Grady, a nurse and bioethicist with the NIH, after they met while treating a patient.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Grady is chief of the Department of Bioethics at the National Institutes of Health Clinical Center.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Together, they have three adult daughters.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] At the time of his retirement, Fauci's annual salary was $480,654, making him the highest paid U.S. federal government employee at the time.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci has described himself as "completely nonpolitical".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] His voter registration shows that he is not affiliated with any political party, although he still votes.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Prior to 2020, he had positive relationships with both Democrats and Republicans, and considered George W.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] According to Fauci, "[Bush's] exact words to me were, 'We have a moral responsibility as a rich nation to not have people suffer and die merely because of where they live and the circumstances in which they were born'".
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Former CDC director and CEO of Resolve to Save Lives, Tom Frieden, said that "I have no idea what his politics are.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] On March 23, 2021, Fauci was admitted as an honorary fellow of the Royal College of Physicians of Ireland.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci has served as one of the principal editors of *Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine*, named on the front cover, from the 11th edition published in 1986, through to the 21st edition, published in 2022.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] He was the editor-in-chief of the 14th and 17th editions.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In addition to receiving an honorary degree in 2015, Fauci was invited to deliver guest remarks on May 21, 2020, for the Johns Hopkins University Class of 2020.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] The College of the Holy Cross renamed its science complex the Anthony S.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] Fauci Integrated Science Complex on June 11, 2022.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In 2025, he received an honorary degree and was invited to speak at the commencement of the humanities and sciences graduates at the University of San Francisco.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/anthony-s-fauci] In 2026, Fauci and his wife Christine Grady gave the keynote address at Macalester College's commencement ceremony, where they both received honorary degrees.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/arthur-bienenstock] He received his B.S. in 1955 and M.S. in 1957 from the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, and a Ph.D. in 1962 from Harvard University.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/arthur-bienenstock] He was the former director of the Stanford Synchrotron Radiation Lightsource from 1978 to 1998.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/arthur-bienenstock] He was vice provost and dean of research at Stanford University from 2003 until 2006.
[src:aaas-philip-hauge-abelson-prize/arthur-bienenstock] He is a former president of the American Physical Society, serving in that role in 2008, and was a recipient of the 2018 AAAS Philip Hauge Abelson Prize.
